        <encodingDesc>
            <projectDesc>
                <p>The TEI file was produced by Till Grallert to provide a list of geo-tagged toponyms
               extracted from a database of sources (Sente XML) and enriched with geo information
               from geonames.org</p>
            </projectDesc>
            <editorialDecl>
                <p>The relation between places, toponyms and their geographic location was recorded
               using TEI P5 XML. Individual 
                    <tei:gi>place</tei:gi>
                    nodes are nested inside 
                    <tei:gi>listPlace</tei:gi>
                    nodes following administrative and topographic structures. Thus the quarters of the
               city of Damascus are recorded as 
                    <tei:gi>place</tei:gi>
                    nodes nested inside a
                    <tei:gi>listPlace</tei:gi>
                    that corresponds to the city. The city of Damascus is then part of
               a 
                    <tei:gi>listPlace</tei:gi>
                    for the county, the district, and the province. Future
               improvements could record different sets of relations in parallel 
                    <tei:gi>listPlace</tei:gi>
                    nodes that all link to a flat tree of places.</p>
                <p>The transscription of Arabic and Ottoman toponyms follows the IJMES paradigm.</p>
                <p>Languages: According to TEI P5 
                    <att>xml:lang</att>
                    should follow BCP 47 
                    <note target="http://www.iana.org/assignments/language-subtag-registry/language-subtag-registry"/>
                    , which specifies for Arabic in Latin transcription &quot;ar-Latn&quot;. The specific type of
               transcription should be added as a private use subtag, i.e. &quot;ar-Latn-x-ijmes&quot; for the
               IJMES transcription of Arabic in Latin script. The tag for Ottoman Turkish is &quot;ota&quot;.
               For transcription in Latin script following an adapted IJMES transcription, it would
               be &quot;ota-Latn-x-ijmes&quot;. The English variant of Latinised Arabic would be &quot;ar-Latn-EN&quot;
               and the French &quot;ar-Latn-FR&quot;</p>
                <p>the structur of the element 
                    <gi>geo</gi>
                    is lat, long</p>
                <p>The pattern of 
                    <att>xml:id</att>
                    s is the following:
                    <list>
                        <item>
                            - no 
                            <att>xml:id</att>
                            : no reference to this place
               could be found in online databases</item>
                        <item>- xml:id starting with lgn [location geonames]
               refer to geoname.org/xml:id</item>
                        <item>- xml:id starting with lwm [location wikimapia] refer to
               wikimapia.org/xml:id</item>
                        <item>- in case of Ottoman provinces named after their capital cities,
               a &quot;p&quot; is amended to the end of the xml:id.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
            </editorialDecl>
